Dear Colleague,

I wanted to share some important information about Title IX and its implications for international university partnerships, especially in light of recent developments concerning Dongguk University in South Korea.

## What is Title IX?

Title IX is a U.S. federal law that protects students from gender-based discrimination and sexual violence in educational settings. What many institutions may not realize is that Title IX responsibilities extend to international partnerships:

• U.S. universities have legal obligations to verify that their international partner institutions maintain appropriate sexual violence prevention systems
• The absence of these protective mechanisms at partner institutions can create legal liability for U.S. academic institutions
• Structural issues like gender imbalance in faculty, lack of reporting systems, and unclear boundaries between academic and commercial entities can constitute Title IX compliance concerns

## Why This Matters Now

This issue has gained attention as several North American universities are reevaluating their partnerships with Dongguk University after documentation of structural risk factors emerged. A global university ranking organization has also escalated these concerns to its management team.

